Still, as with adding back ports to these streamlined laptops, you can get external hardware to do the job. The ports on some newer laptop models may be limited to USB-C plugs only, so make sure you know what type of connectors work with the laptop you plan to buy. (If your preferred disc drive model does not have a connector that matches your laptop, you can get an adapter.)
Major hardware makers, including Apple and Dell, sell their own external disc drives designed to work with their laptops, but you can likely find less expensive hardware from other manufacturers. Some add-on drives can be a little too cheap, however, so be sure to read the reviews before buying.
Wirecutter, a product recommendation site owned by The New York Times, tested a variety of external disc drives and picked a $25 portable CD/DVD burner made by LG Electronics (the LG GP65NB60 model) as its top choice. For those who want Blu-ray disc compatibility along with CD and DVD playback and recording, the site recommends the Pioneer BDR-XD05B, which sells for around $90.
